  "intermediate_belief": "If I let my guard down or reconnect with someone who has hurt me, I will end up being harmed again. I must protect myself by keeping strict boundaries, even if it means being alone. Trusting others is dangerous because it leads to disappointment or betrayal.",
  "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I can't make relationships work or keep getting hurt, it means I'm fundamentally flawed and things will never get better for me.",
  "coping_strategies": "The client tends to avoid reconnecting with people who have caused harm, using withdrawal and strict boundary-setting as protective strategies. There is a pattern of rumination about past conflicts and a tendency to respond to perceived threats with aggression or defensiveness. These coping mechanisms help the client feel safer in the short term but may reinforce isolation and mistrust.",
  "situation": "Considering reconnecting with an estranged person who previously caused harm. Deciding not to reconnect as a self-protective choice.",
  "auto_thought": "If I let this person back into my life, I'll just get hurt again. I can't trust them and I need to protect myself.",
